04205nam a22006615i 9780292796829DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927968297 a10.7560/7065762doi  a(DE-B1597)587038  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPA6825b.S63 2005eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a873/.012221 aSmith, Riggs Alden, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Primacy of Vision in Virgil's Aeneid /cRiggs Alden Smith. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (271 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tText and Art Acknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tChapter 1 Prophaenomena ad Vergilium -- tChapter 2 Ruse and Revelation: Visions of the Divine and the Telos of Narrative -- tChapter 3 Vision Past and Future -- tChapter 4 Hic amor: Love, Vision, and Destiny -- tChapter 5 Vidi, Vici: Vision’s Victory and the Telos of Narrative -- tChapter 6 Conclusion: Ante ora parentum -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tSubject Index -- tIndex Locorum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of the masterpieces of Latin and, indeed, world literature, Virgil's Aeneid was written during the Augustan "renaissance" of architecture, art, and literature that redefined the Roman world in the early years of the empire. This period was marked by a transition from the use of rhetoric as a means of public persuasion to the use of images to display imperial power. Taking a fresh approach to Virgil's epic poem, Riggs Alden Smith argues that the Aeneid fundamentally participates in the Augustan shift from rhetoric to imagery because it gives primacy to vision over speech as the principal means of gathering and conveying information as it recounts the heroic adventures of Aeneas, the legendary founder of Rome. Working from the theories of French phenomenologist Maurice Merleau-Ponty, Smith characterizes Aeneas as a voyant-visible, a person who both sees and is seen and who approaches the world through the faculty of vision. Engaging in close readings of key episodes throughout the poem, Smith shows how Aeneas repeatedly acts on what he sees rather than what he hears. Smith views Aeneas' final act of slaying Turnus, a character associated with the power of oratory, as the victory of vision over rhetoric, a triumph that reflects the ascendancy of visual symbols within Augustan society. Smith's new interpretation of the predominance of vision in the Aeneid makes it plain that Virgil's epic contributes to a new visual culture and a new mythology of Imperial Rome.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAeneas (Legendary character) in literature. 0aArt and literaturezRome. 0aEpic poetry, LatinxHistory and criticism. 0aVision in literature. 0aVisions in literature. 0aVisual perception in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796829423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796829/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK